\begin_layout Abstract
We present a mathematical framework based on quantum interval-valued probability
 measures to study the effect of experimental imperfections and finite precision
 measurements on defining aspects of quantum mechanics such as contextuality
 and the Born rule.
 While foundational results such as the Kochen-Specker and Gleason theorems
 fail to hold in general in a world with limited resources, when we allow
 infinite precision, their validity is recovered.
 However, we are able to use the interval-valued framework to establish
 bounds on the validity of those theorems in realistic experimental environments.
 In this way, not only can we quantify the idea of finite-precision measurement
 within our theory, but we can also suggest a possible resolution of the
 Meyer-Mermin debate on the impact of finite-precision measurement on the
 Kochen-Specker theorem.
 
\end_layout

