\begin_layout Standard
We will start by reviewing IVPMs in the classical setting and then propose
 our quantum generalization.
 In the classical setting, there are several proposals for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

imprecise probabilities
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
citep{Dempster1967,Shafer1976,GilboaSchmeidler1994,Marinacci1999,Weichselberger2
000,JamisonLodwick2004,HuberRonchetti2009,Grabisch2016}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Although these proposals differ in some details, they all share the fact
 that the probability 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)$
\end_inset

 of an event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is generalized from a single 
\emph on
real number
\emph default
 to an 
\emph on
interval
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $[\ell,r]$
\end_inset

 where
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 intuitively corresponds to the strength of evidence for the event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $1-r$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the strength of evidence against the same event.
 More generally, this inverval would be interpreted as the Guassian width
 of a probability distribution, but for notational convenience we will continue
 in the following to write this as a definite interval.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
yutsung{
\end_layout

\end_inset

Check the interpretation in the statistics literature
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "HuberRonchetti2009"

\end_inset

! Or we may need to prove it could be interpreted as Gaussian width by ourselves...
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The collection of intervals used in the definition of a probability measure
 must satisfy certain properties that we explain next.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, for each interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[\ell,r]$
\end_inset

 we have the natural constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\ell\leq r\leq1$
\end_inset

 that guarantees that every element of the interval can be interpreted as
 a conventional probability.
 We also include 
\begin_inset Formula $\imposs=[0,0]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\necess=[1,1]$
\end_inset

 as limiting intervals to refer to the probability of impossible events
 (e.g., the null event) and events that are certain (e.g., the event covering
 the entire sample space).
 For each interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[\ell,r]$
\end_inset

, we also need the dual interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[1-r,1-\ell]$
\end_inset

 so that if one interval refers to the probability of an event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, the dual refers to the probability of the event's complement 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if we discover as a result of an experiment that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)=[0.2,0.3]$
\end_inset

 for some event
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, we may conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\overline{E})=[0.7,0.8]$
\end_inset

 for the complementary event 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}$
\end_inset

.
 In addition to these simple conditions, there are some subtle conditions
 on how intervals are combined, which we discuss next.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 be two disjoint events with probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1})=[\ell_{1},r_{1}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{2})=[\ell_{2},r_{2}]$
\end_inset

.
 A first attempt at calculating the probability of the combined event that
 
\emph on
either
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 occurs might be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1}\cup E_{2})=[\ell_{1}+\ell_{2},r_{1}+r_{2}]$
\end_inset

.
 In some cases, this is indeed a sensible definition.
 For example, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1})=[0.1,0.2]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{2})=[0.3,0.4]$
\end_inset

 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1}\cup E_{2})=[0.4,0.6]$
\end_inset

.
 But consider an event 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)=[0.2,0.3]$
\end_inset

 and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\overline{E})=[0.7,0.8]$
\end_inset

.
 The two events 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}$
\end_inset

 are disjoint; the naïve addition of intervals would give 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E\cup\overline{E})=[0.9,1.1]$
\end_inset

 which is not a valid probability interval.
 Moreover the event 
\begin_inset Formula $E\cup\overline{E}$
\end_inset

 is the entire space; its probability interval should be 
\begin_inset Formula $\necess$
\end_inset

 which is sharper than 
\begin_inset Formula $[0.9,1.1]$
\end_inset

.
 The problem is that the two intervals are correlated: there is more information
 in the combined event than in each event separately.
 In our example, even though the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 can be anywhere in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $[0.2,0.3]$
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 probability of
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\overline{E}$
\end_inset

 can be in anywhere in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $[0.7,0.8]$
\end_inset

, the values are not independent.
 Any value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)\leq0.25$
\end_inset

 will force 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\overline{E})\geq0.75$
\end_inset

.
 To account for such subtleties, the axioms of interval-valued probability
 do not use a strict equality for the combination of disjoint events.
 The correct constraint regarding the probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}\cup E_{2}$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

 are disjoint is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1}\cup E_{2})\subseteq[\ell_{1}+\ell_{2},r_{1}+r_{2}]$
\end_inset

 which, in combination with the requirement for the event of the entire
 space would force 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E\cup\overline{E})$
\end_inset

 to always be 
\begin_inset Formula $\necess$
\end_inset

 irrespective of the particular assignments of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E)$
\end_inset

 or
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mu(\overline{E})$
\end_inset

.
 Parallel arguments can be made interpreting 
\begin_inset Formula $[\ell,r]$
\end_inset

 as Gaussian width, but will be omitted as no essential new information
 seems to be introduced.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When combining non-disjoint events, there is a further subtlety whose resolution
 will give us the final general condition for IVPMs.
 For general, not necessarily disjoint, events 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}$
\end_inset

, we have: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu(E_{1}\cup E_{2})+\mu(E_{1}\cap E_{2})\subseteq\mu(E_{1})+\mu(E_{2})\label{eq:classicalconvex}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

which is a generalization of the classical inclusion-exclusion principle
 that uses 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $=$
\end_inset

 for the same reason as before.
 The new condition, known as 
\emph on
convexity
\emph default

\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Shapley1971,GilboaSchmeidler1994,Marinacci1999,Grabisch2016"

\end_inset

, reduces to the previously motivated condition when the events are disjoint,
 i.e., when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu(E_{1}\cap E_{2})=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

